          handling card transactions
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>SOC 2:</strong> Security, availability, and confidentiality controls
          for service organizations
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Our Security Framework</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>NIST Cybersecurity Framework:</strong> Identify, Protect, Detect,
          Respond, Recover
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>CIS Controls:</strong> Prioritized set of actions to protect organizations
          from cyber attacks
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>OWASP Guidelines:</strong> Security best practices for web and mobile
          applications
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Zero Trust Architecture:</strong> "Never trust, always verify" approach
          to network security
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="faq-container">
        <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p class="section-subtitle">
          Common questions about our custom software development process in the
          UAE.
        </p>

        <div class="faq-list">
          <details>
            <summary
              >What is a penetration test and does my business need one?</summary
            >
            <p>
              A penetration test (pen test) is a simulated, authorized cyber
              attack on your systems, conducted by security experts to identify
              vulnerabilities before real attackers do. It goes beyond automated
              scanning to test how vulnerabilities can be chained together and
              exploited in practice. Most businesses handling sensitive customer
              data, financial transactions, or operating in regulated industries
              should conduct penetration testing at least annually, and after
              any significant system change.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >What cybersecurity regulations apply to businesses in the UAE?</summary
            >
            <p>
              Key frameworks include the UAE National Cybersecurity Strategy,
              the Dubai Electronic Security Center (DESC) standards (mandatory
              for Dubai government entities and suppliers), the Abu Dhabi
              Digital Authority (ADDA) cybersecurity standards, and
              sector-specific requirements from the UAE Central Bank for
              financial institutions. For businesses handling EU citizen data,
              GDPR also applies regardless of where the company is based.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>How long does a security assessment take?</summary>
            <p>
              A vulnerability assessment of a standard web application typically
              takes three to five days. A comprehensive penetration test of a
              larger environment — including web apps, APIs, internal network,
              and mobile apps — generally takes two to three weeks. A full
              organizational security audit, including policies, procedures, and
              technical controls, takes four to six weeks. We scope the
              engagement based on your specific environment and risk profile.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >What is the difference between a vulnerability assessment and a
              penetration test?</summary
            >
            <p>
              A vulnerability assessment identifies and classifies security
              weaknesses in your systems, primarily through automated scanning
              and manual review. A penetration test goes further — a security
              professional actively attempts to exploit those vulnerabilities to
              understand what an attacker could actually access. The assessment
              tells you what might be broken; the pen test tells you what
              someone could do if it is.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >Can you help us respond to an active security incident?</summary
            >
            <p>
              If you are experiencing an active breach or suspect a compromise,
              contact us immediately. We provide incident response services
              including forensic investigation, containment, eradication of the
              threat, and recovery planning. We also help document the incident
              for regulatory reporting requirements.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Do you offer ongoing security monitoring?</summary>
            <p>
              Yes. Beyond point-in-time assessments, we offer managed security
              services including continuous vulnerability monitoring, security
              event alerting, and periodic review cycles. This is particularly
              valuable for businesses that lack an in-house security operations
              capability.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

